Absolutely decadent in the best possible way. Truly comfort food, but just pray that you don't need comfort too often in life because I am not sure there was anything that wasn't terrible for parts of your body besides your taste buds. I ordered the ribs, and I thought they were lacking a bit in meat, but that's not really the fault of the establishment so much as my own self for forgetting that ribs are mostly bone. The mac and cheese was delightful, though, and I really recommend it if you can look past the amount of fat you are likely inhaling. One thing that I have to say, though, is that the service is exquisite. My friend's order of French onion soup was about 5-10 minutes late, and they comped us for it without any sort of request from us. Really made an impression, and really made me want to return (that, and the fried chicken I didn't get to taste).

Everything we ordered was delicious. We started with the beignet flight which I highly recommend. First time trying a savory beignet and every bite was as good as the first. We also ordered the shrimp with goat cheese omelette which was pretty good and very filling.

The brunch menu is unique and very tasty. I would recommend arriving as early as possible because the wait is absurd. That said, the food is worth the wait and it gets to your table fast.

Brenda Brenda Brenda !!! She knows how to serve a fantastic breakfast ! I have never had a desire to try grittz the name alone isn't appetizing to me. Shrimp and Grittz was the hands down bow down beat introduction I could ask for! This Davy dish was hearty perfect blend of savory sweet & spicy kicker to keep me full and wanting more even thought I didn't have enough room. Excellent choice for breakfast and I'm eager to try a din din dish next !

They're now open for lunch and dinner, and who'd a thunk it - they have a kick ass vegan option right on their everyday menu! It's not hidden from view, no need to whisper into your server's ear inquiring about an option for plant based eaters for fear of being ridiculed by those sitting around you, and no winks, gun barrel hand motions, or secret handshakes - the Vegan Josephine is a legitimate lunch and dinner choice with Brenda's new and expanded hours. Score! With all that enthusiasm, you're probably wondering how it was, huh? Well, let me tell you: it was bomb! It's basically a tofu Sloppy Joe on a toasted potato roll with your choice of french fries or slaw (not vegan) on the side. I actually asked about having mixed greens instead of either of those options, and I got docked an additional $1 which I thought was a bit whack... but I suppose it doesn't completely overshadow my excitement over that fantastic sandwich option!

Flavors were good but the portions were large and the food is very rich. I almost had to be wheeled out of the restaurant at 10AM because my breakfast made me feel sleepy. Luckily, I was visiting from So Cal so I guess I wont get too fat from eating here all the time.

Came here with a friend recently after a trip to the movies. We were hungry, ready to try everything and chow down. Unfortunately, Brenda's had this new menu thing going on. Certain hours of the day they only have certain menus items. My friend and I were craving items that were on the original menu but missing from the 3-5pm menu. Besides missing out over stuffing ourselves, we enjoyed the food and atmosphere. It was 3:30, no wait. Place was busy but were seated right away. Service was attentive and sweet. I appreciate that. My friend got the burger since the salad she had planned on getting with missing from the 3-5 menu. She liked it. I got the hush puppies. They were great!!! Until they got cold, then they were not so great. My shrimp Po boy made up for it though. Perfectly cooked shrimp, excellent cole slaw and the bread was dusted with melted butter and grilled to give it a nice toasted texture. Hella, hella good. However, I got the chocolate beignets for dessert and they were burnt! The outside pastry and inside chocolate were both burnt. We were both so stuffed we took a lot of stuff to go. So when I got home it was too late to ask for non burnt beignets. Next time I will make sure they aren't. And I will definitely be coming back for the shrimp Po boy. For a place that is often extremely busy with customers down the block, they do a good job. I appreciate that. Thanks Brenda!!

This place combines two of my favorite cuisines: French and Soul. Ahh! Got here around 1:30PM on a Saturday, and there was a decent line in front of us already, but suprisingly we didn't have to wait that long to get seated. Some kind of magic keeps their tables turning over fast - maybe how each table is only 2 people large and they can keep rearranging them to suit the size of each party. Got the watermelon tea, the crawfish beignets, and the catfish eggs benedict. The waitress kind of gave me a look for ordering so much food, but in my defense, all of the beignets I've seen up to this point are small. This beignet was HUGE!! Like..bigger than my iphone. It was so yummy though, with crawfish and cheese(?) inside. I can definitely see why it made it on the 7x7 list. The eggs benedict were also good, but average compared to the ones i've had everywhere else. I had to take a bunch of my food home, and it wasn't until the next day when I went to reheat my beignet that I realized how much oil was in the thing - it had completely soaked through the to-go bag! Kind of gross. But it was still delicious! Some kind of magic for sure.

Pretty darn good chicken! It's battered and fried to a golden brown. The brine/ seasoning actually penetrates the meat... leaving it wonderfully juicy and full of flavor! Also If your expecting KFC-sized chicken pieces, you'll need to order more. These pieces are smaller... so they'll go fast. The wait here is a bit long and the parking quite difficult. I found take-out to be the next best thing.

My second time at Brenda's my namesake and she did not disappoint. I got the ribs. It came with greens and Mac and cheese. The greens were under the ribs. So the bbq sauce was all up and through the greens. So delicious. I literally can still taste it. The Mac and cheese was cheesy but I thought it needed a pinch of salt. My boyfriend got the BFC which is the fried chicken dinner with greens and a biscuit. The chicken was delicious as well. The biscuit came with some jam, which was super delicious. The space is a bit tight but it's not uncomfortable. I still felt like I could have an intimate conversation with my boyfriend. We had to street park. Surprisingly it was difficult to find free metered parking 2 blocks away. I love this restaurant and I will always stop by when I'm in the Bay!

I really love this place. I've been here for brunch, lunch, and their "in-betweens" several times. I think I might be addicted to their Andouille & Cheddar omelette. Next step is to find an excuse to bring friends.

I recall it being great, but it's unclear these days. The grits are always a delight. Comfort food makes me smile.

If you were raised in the south, this place will surely disappoint. Since my best friend was raised in Baton Rouge and a cajun food lover through and through, I was thrilled to take her to Brenda's given the review and recommendations from my friends. Sad to say, the food was a complete let down (mind you we were starving by the time we got seated!). BEIGNET FLIGHT: Best thing this place has to offer. Good, but no where near authentic. The dough was a lot more dense than what you find in Louisiana. PULLED PORK BENEDICT: For something that made it to the special menu, there was nothing special about this one. Shiesty on the pulled pork that wasn't even all that flavor packed to begin with...come on now! SHRIMP AND GRITS: Extra buttery and cheesy...two ingredients that usually redeem any dish. But why did the shrimp taste fishy in a weird way? WATERMELON TEA: Good but on the too sweet side. We had such high hopes for some great soul food!

One of my first forays into fine dining in the TL, I met up with a friend who happened to be back in town after several years of absence. First off, to clarify, Brenda's IS wheelchair accessible, so please ignore the fact that it says otherwise. Granted, it's a bit cramped inside, so that may pose an issue, but there are no steps or stairs that would otherwise prevent access. We ended up ordering a crawfish beignet for a starter, BFC and po'boy for our entrees, and a sampler set of dessert beignets for dessert. The crawfish beignet had some good flavor, but the dough itself was too dense and lackluster. Same thing goes for the dessert beignets: too doughy, and not fluffy or airy enough (go check out Angeline's Louisiana Kitchen in Berkeley if you want amazing dessert beignets). However, if you still insist on trying them, make sure to get the sampler, rather than ordering individually, as, for an extra $1.50, you get two more full-sized beignets. As for the BFC... the biscuit itself was awesome, the collard greens were tasty, the jam to accompany the chicken was interesting, but the chicken itself was not particularly impressive. My friend's po'boy was a bit tastier, but also fairly unimpressive. I can't really see myself making a point of coming out here just to eat here again, but, if I'm in the area and craving soul food, there's a chance I'd drop in, so they fall into the low end of my three star restaurants. But, really, there's better soul food in the Bay.

My husband and I make it a point to get breakfast here every time we visit SF. Go early and get your name on that holy chalk board, or you'll be waiting quite a while. But, even if you do have a wait, it's worth it. Get those grits. Get that biscuit. Get that chicory coffee. Try not to slap your mama! Mmmm...

Crawfish beignets are amazing! They also had sweet potato pancakes that were one of the specials for the day - can taste the sweet potatoes. Sooooo good!

I feel like this place is better for smaller groups as they get in much quicker. Once we got our table though our waitress was incredibly rude. First off, none of us had ever been there before so we started off by ordering the beignets. Our waitress rudely says "Ok you guys can't have that many beignets. That's too many." Umm ok. There are a million more polite ways to tell us that more than one comes on a plate (maybe it says that on the menu but we wanted to order as soon as we got in after waiting for so long.) Also WE ARE PAYING FOR THEM. So why does it matter how many we order? If there is a limit per table I didn't see it. They literally came out like 5 minutes after we ordered them so it doesn't seem like it takes a long time to make them. After we had all ordered except our one friend who doesn't speak/read english that well took more than 30 seconds to order from the menu while she angrily glared at him and she goes "Ok you're going to have to hurry up buddy." So he ended up just randomly picking something off the menu. It would've been nice if she had suggested something good or said anything else honestly. On the plus side the beignets are actually really really good. The food we ordered off the brunch menu was good though I'm not sure if it's worth over an hour wait. I feel like if we had gone to this place on a different time on a different day the experience would've been so much better. I regret not complaining to the manager about that waitress. I don't plan on coming back.

    Hmmm, I guess I wasn't as blown away by Brenda's as most others seem to be.

    I came here with a group of friends (4 top), for some weekend brunch action. Pumped on the series of glowing reviews I'd read, I was ready for some serious brunch grind.

    Their food was pretty good. The gumbo is not to be missed, and the catfish benedict was killer (to both my taste buds, and my waistline). I'd go back anytime for either of those dishes. Unfortunately, neither of those items were my own. I had the hangtown fry, and it wasn't quite what I had imagined. I guess it's my own fault for ordering a fried oyster and bacon scramble first thing in the morning... but I was expecting something different. It's a regional classic, I learned (invented during the Gold Rush), so that's pretty notable, I suppose.

    The place is really, really small... so the wait was horrendous. Not sure how we didn't go crazy, but we eventually waited over 2 hours to get seated. I usually have zero patience for extended waits at restaurants, but because Brenda's has been on my radar for a loooooooong time, I was down for the challenge. Perhaps that's why I ended up not loving my experience? I dunno, but I don't foresee myself lounging this long before eating anytime soon.

    Also, unless I missed something, they don't serve any adult libations during brunch. That's a bit of a bummer.

    If I find myself randomly driving by and there aren't 30 people waiting for a seat, I'd probably stop in again. But that downtime is for the birds as far as I'm concerned. I did see people prepared for the wait, though... so you might want to come armed with DIY mimosas or hand rolled cigarettes with something other than tobacco inside. Seemed to be the trend among everyone around me.

    One of my first forays into fine dining in the TL, I met up with a friend who happened to be back in town after several years of absence. First off, to clarify, Brenda's IS wheelchair accessible, so please ignore the fact that it says otherwise. Granted, it's a bit cramped inside, so that may pose an issue, but there are no steps or stairs that would otherwise prevent access.

    We ended up ordering a crawfish beignet for a starter, BFC and po'boy for our entrees, and a sampler set of dessert beignets for dessert. The crawfish beignet had some good flavor, but the dough itself was too dense and lackluster. Same thing goes for the dessert beignets: too doughy, and not fluffy or airy enough (go check out Angeline's Louisiana Kitchen in Berkeley if you want amazing dessert beignets). However, if you still insist on trying them, make sure to get the sampler, rather than ordering individually, as, for an extra $1.50, you get two more full-sized beignets.

    As for the BFC... the biscuit itself was awesome, the collard greens were tasty, the jam to accompany the chicken was interesting, but the chicken itself was not particularly impressive. My friend's po'boy was a bit tastier, but also fairly unimpressive. I can't really see myself making a point of coming out here just to eat here again, but, if I'm in the area and craving soul food, there's a chance I'd drop in, so they fall into the low end of my three star restaurants. But, really, there's better soul food in the Bay.

I feel like this place is better for smaller groups as they get in much quicker.

    Once we got our table though our waitress was incredibly rude.

    First off, none of us had ever been there before so we started off by ordering the beignets. Our waitress rudely says "Ok you guys can't have that many beignets. That's too many." Umm ok. There are a million more polite ways to tell us that more than one comes on a plate (maybe it says that on the menu but we wanted to order as soon as we got in after waiting for so long.) Also WE ARE PAYING FOR THEM. So why does it matter how many we order? If there is a limit per table I didn't see it. They literally came out like 5 minutes after we ordered them so it doesn't seem like it takes a long time to make them.

    After we had all ordered except our one friend who doesn't speak/read english that well took more than 30 seconds to order from the menu while she angrily glared at him and she goes "Ok you're going to have to hurry up buddy."  So he ended up just randomly picking something off the menu. It would've been nice if she had suggested something good or said anything else honestly.

    On the plus side the beignets are actually really really good. The food we ordered off the brunch menu was good though I'm not sure if it's worth over an hour wait.

    I feel like if we had gone to this place on a different time on a different day the experience would've been so much better. I regret not complaining to the manager about that waitress. I don't plan on coming back.
